John Edward: Language skills are a key skill for global citizens
Traditionally, the learning outcomes of private schools in Scotland have been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of the good test results, which have been enhanced by individual and community success in sport, art, music and other community projects.
These schools of more than 30 000 students are located across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), and aim to provide a high-quality service to their students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for their chosen career, postgraduate and higher education, as well as for world citizenship.
As an operator in the field of education who can design and implement tailored study content, we have noticed the role of languages as a popular and desirable subject in continuing education institutions.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak in a language that he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his or her own language, the message goes to his or her heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language if we want to establish relationships of trust with people from other countries.
From the latest test results this year, we find that languages are at the top of the list for the pass rate among private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade A.
The data were collected from 74 CIS schools, and found that 72% of students who received the highest grade of A, 72% studied Mandarin Chinese, 72% studied German, 69% studied French, and 63% studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are considered to be of the same value as natural sciences (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school curriculum and elsewhere.
Based on a survey conducted by the UK Employment Office in 2014, it was found that 17% of situations where an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee were explained by lack of language skills.
Therefore, the development of language skills is even more necessary for the promotion of future career development of young people.
The more possible tasks require language skills, the more relevant these skills will be in the global world.
If a person has studied another language, he/she will have an advantage in the future for this lifelong skill, regardless of which career he/she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts the language-oriented person ahead of the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013, more than 4 000 UK adults were unable to speak in a foreign language, and French was the only language known to a double-digit number of 15%.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Especially the knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better chance to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
A number of schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are likely to be important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Despite your child’s interests, there are always several language options taught by specialized teachers in private schools.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
In this time, it cannot be denied that languages in the international business environment will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be seen as “international communication skills”.
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and a high level of education for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Private School Council (SCIS)
