Charles Czeisler, a professor of medical sciences at Harvard University who works in sleep research at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, believes the course is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, ‘Why do I only hear about it now, in my last year of study?’
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I thought was surprising,” he told Telegraph in an interview.
This course, organized for the first time this year, will guide students on how the right sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Dr Paul Barreira, professor of medical sciences at Harvard University and vice president of health services at the University, says that the university ended up organising a course after they had heard that students were suffering from severe sleep deficits during the study week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, and thus get information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second part, participants will learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
The map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
We know that this does not have an immediate impact on student behaviour.
However, we believe that they have the right to know about these things in exactly the same way that they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking,” adds Professor Czeisler.
All night long student marathons are still a matter of pride, according to Professor Czeisler, and modern technology and the ever-growing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Getting adequate and high-quality sleep should be a student’s ‘secret weapon’ against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a condition resembling starvation in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry,” the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemical and physical psychology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his first courses in Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave a boost to the organization of a comprehensive course for all campus students.
He hopes that all doctoral students will be able to complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students also set an alarm to remind them of bedtime not only to wake up in the morning, but also to keep in mind the adverse effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting on the “blue light” circadian rhythm, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
