Next page of our “Sunday Morning” almanac: September 30, 1882. Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger, the future physicist, was born in Germany today 136 years ago.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which later led to the development of a device known as a geigerometer.
The method became one of the pillars of science, and also a central concept of pop culture. For example, the 1950 film “Coronado’s Clocks” in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans present scientists who seem to be quite herders:
Man: “What on earth is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geigerometer. It’s used to find radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put your headphones in your ears, you can really hear the effect of radioactive radiation in the minerals.”
Evans: “Look, it’s really ticking now!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945 a few days before his 63rd birthday.
However, an invention that bears his name still lives.
New cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
The new cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognise malignant cells as part of treatment
In the method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory
After treatment, the cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ the proteins typical of multiple cancers
The trial vaccine has shown promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
For example, the cancer cells of an ovarian cancer patient disappeared within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognise malignant cells.
In the method, the resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of several cancers. The modified cells are finally injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky from the National Institute for Cancer in Bethesda, USA, describes the method: “Based on our findings, this is a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 “directs the growth of several types of cancer,” explains Professor Berzofsky. “These include breast cancer and cancers of the ovaries, lungs and colon.”
A similar approach – taking resistant cells from the patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells – has also produced results in the treatment of a type of leukaemia.
