The tsunami also hit the western part of Donggala in 1996 killing nine people.
Indonesia is seismically located in the active Pacific Ring of Fire and is often hit by earthquakes.
Some of the most serious earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A severe earthquake in northern Sumatra on the west coast of Aceh province in Indonesia caused a tsunami on December 26 that struck 14 states and killed 226 000 people on the coasts of the Indian Ocean. More than half of the victims were in the Aceh region.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra at the end of March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias in the coastal waters of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude quake struck south of the most populated island of Indonesia, Java, causing a tsunami that struck the island's southern coast killing nearly 700 people.
2009: The 7.6 magnitude quake struck the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1 100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude quake struck one of the Sumatra islands of Mentawai, causing a ten-meter-high tsunami that destroyed several villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A superficial quake struck Aceh in the Pidie Jaya region, causing destruction and panic as people remember the enormous damage caused by the 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time there was no tsunami, but more than a hundred people died in the collapse of the buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia and killed more than 500 people, mainly in the northern part of the island.
